Cross-section Integration: DLPFC

Overview

This R Markdown document runs a cross-section integration workflow using the DaVinci package on multiple DLPFC slices. It includes preprocessing, cross-section integration, visualization of latent variables, and clustering. Adjust file paths, parameters, and plotting options to suit your environment and desired level of detail.

Setup

Load required packages and set the working directory. Change the setwd() path to where your data/ folder is located if necessary.

library(DaVinci)
library(ggpubr)

setwd("~/For_Tutorial/DLPFC/")

Configuration

Set minimal configuration options for preprocessing. normalize.version controls preprocessing choices (e.g., gene for RNA, or several LSI_* options for ATAC-like preprocessing).

normalize.version <- "gene"  # options: "gene", "LSI_1", "LSI_2", "LSI_3"

Load data & preprocess per sample

This section reads RDS files from data/. Each RDS file should contain at least mat (gene-by-spot matrix of raw counts) and coor (spot-by-(x,y) coordinate matrix with columns array_row and array_col). The loop preprocesses each sample according to normalize.version and stores results in Y.list, L.list, and coor.list.

data.dir <- "~/For_Tutorial/DLPFC/data/"

file.list <- list.files(data.dir)
file.list <- file.list[grepl(".RDS", file.list)]
dataset.opts <- gsub(".RDS", "", file.list)

Y.list <- list()
L.list <- list()
coor.list <- list()

for (ii in seq_along(dataset.opts)) {
  input.file <- paste0(data.dir, file.list[ii])
  input <- readRDS(input.file)
  
  mat <- input$mat
  coor <- input$coor
  
  if (normalize.version == "gene") {
    fin <- preprocess(mat, 
                      coor, 
                      type = "rna", 
                      graph.opt = "Tri.mesh", 
                      frac.thr = 0.95)

  } else if (normalize.version == "LSI_1") {
    fin <- preprocess(mat, 
                      coor, 
                      type = "atac", 
                      graph.opt = "Tri.mesh",
                      LSI.method = "1", 
                      LSI.scale.factor = 1e5, 
                      LSI.peak.filter.thr = 0.95)

  } else if (normalize.version == "LSI_2") {
    fin <- preprocess(mat, 
                      coor, 
                      type = "atac", 
                      graph.opt = "Tri.mesh",
                      LSI.method = "2", 
                      LSI.scale.factor = 1e5, 
                      LSI.peak.filter.thr = 0.95)

  } else if (normalize.version == "LSI_3") {
    fin <- preprocess(mat, 
                      coor, 
                      type = "atac", 
                      graph.opt = "Tri.mesh",
                      LSI.method = "3", 
                      LSI.scale.factor = 1e5, 
                      LSI.peak.filter.thr = 0.95)
  }
  
  Y.list[[ii]] <- fin$mat
  L.list[[ii]] <- fin$L
  coor.list[[ii]] <- fin$coor
}

Quick demo: subset of the sections

For a quick demo run or debugging, we restrict to the first two sections. Remove or modify this section to run on all samples.

dataset.opts <- dataset.opts[1:2]
Y.list <- Y.list[1:2]
L.list <- L.list[1:2]
coor.list <- coor.list[1:2]

Cross-section integration

This step achives the cross-section integration via a wrapper function Horizontal.Integration.Assemble. k.arg.list is a list of candidate numbers of latent variables for identifying robust latent variables. The example uses a short list for demo. Note: The wrapper function Horizontal.Integration.Assemble is readily parallelizable and will be implemented in a future release.

HI.res <- Horizontal.Integration.Assemble(
  dataset.opts = dataset.opts,
  Y.list  = Y.list,
  L.list  = L.list,
  coor.list = coor.list,
  k.arg.list = c(4, 6, 8)  # candidate k values; extend if needed
)

Extract integrated latent matrix and section mapping

HI.res$mat contains integrated latent variables, and HI.res$mat.slice.id maps each column/spot to its original section. Well use these for clustering and visualization.

mat <- HI.res$mat
mat.slice.id <- HI.res$mat.slice.id

Visualize latent variables by section

Use scatter.FeaturePlot.list() to visualize latent variable patterns across sections. The first call displays everything on a single page. The second call returns individual plot objects for further arrangement or saving.

#visualize everything on the same page directly
#scatter.FeaturePlot.list(mat, coor.list, mat.slice.id, dataset.opts)

names(coor.list) <- dataset.opts

# visualize separately by LV (returns list of plots)
plot.list <- scatter.FeaturePlot.list(mat, 
                                      coor.list, 
                                      mat.slice.id, 
                                      dataset.opts,
                                      pt.size = 0.5, 
                                      return.obj = TRUE, single.obj = FALSE, 
                          orientation = "y-x")

#Arrange first LV across sections
ggarrange(plotlist = plot.list[[1]])

Inspect loadings

The HI.res$integration.res$loading object contains gene loadings associated with each LV.

loading <- HI.res$integration.res$loading
# Example: show top 20 genes for the first sample and first LV (if present)

if (!is.null(loading) && length(loading) >= 1) {
  print(head(sort(loading[[1]], decreasing = TRUE), 20))
}

Clustering options (multiple workflows)

DaVinci provides multiple clustering workflows. We demonstrate three options: Louvain clustering with resolution sweep, Louvain with direct number-of-clusters control, and mclust. After clustering, an optional refinement step Niche.report.finetune() smooths clusters spatially.

Option 1: Louvain clustering (resolution sweep)

res.niche <- Niche.report(mat, 
                          method = "louvain", 
                          L2.opt = TRUE,
                          resolution.args = c(0.5, 1), verbose = FALSE)

res.niche.refine <- Niche.report.finetune(res.niche$niche.list, dataset.opts, coor.list, mat.slice.id)

# visualize refined clusters (example using resolution = 0.5)
cluster.RNA <- res.niche.refine[[1]]
scatter.DiscretePlot.list(cluster.RNA, 
                          coor.list, 
                          mat.slice.id, 
                          dataset.opts,
                          pt.size = 0.5, 
                          orientation = "y-x")

Option 2: Louvain clustering (fixed number of clusters)

res.niche <- Niche.report(mat, 
                          method = "louvain", 
                          L2.opt = TRUE,
                          num.cluster.args = c(7, 10), verbose = FALSE)
res.niche.refine <- Niche.report.finetune(res.niche$niche.list, dataset.opts, coor.list, mat.slice.id)

cluster.RNA <- res.niche.refine[[1]] 
scatter.DiscretePlot.list(cluster.RNA, 
                          coor.list, 
                          mat.slice.id, 
                          dataset.opts, 
                          pt.size = 0.5, 
                          orientation = "y-x")

Option 3: mclust

res.niche <- Niche.report(mat, 
                          method = "mclust", 
                          L2.opt = TRUE, 
                          num.cluster.args = c(7, 10), 
                          verbose = FALSE)
res.niche.refine <- Niche.report.finetune(res.niche$niche.list, dataset.opts, coor.list, mat.slice.id)

cluster.RNA <- res.niche.refine[[1]]
scatter.DiscretePlot.list(cluster.RNA, 
                          coor.list, 
                          mat.slice.id, 
                          dataset.opts, 
                          pt.size = 0.5, 
                          orientation = "y-x")
